ommunicate her own healthcare decisions but wants to ensure her wishes are respected if her condition deteriorates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of a medical power of attorney / substitute decision maker?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Overrides the person\u0027s existing advance care directive","Manages financial and property matters only","Provides medical treatment recommendations to other doctors","Makes immediate healthcare decisions regardless of current capacity","Becomes the legal decision-maker when the person loses capacity"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emedical power of attorney / substitute decision maker becomes the legal decision maker when the person loses capacity\u003C/strong\u003E to make or communicate their own healthcare decisions. This appointed person must make decisions based on the known wishes and values of the person who appointed them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMakes immediate healthcare decisions regardless of current capacity\u003C/strong\u003E - The medical power of attorney only takes effect when the person loses decision-making capacity; while the person retains capacity, they make their own decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverrides the person\u0027s existing advance care directive\u003C/strong\u003E - The medical power of attorney must consider and respect any existing advance care directive when making decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManages financial and property matters only\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes an enduring power of attorney for financial matters, which is separate from medical decision-making authority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvides medical treatment recommendations to other doctors\u003C/strong\u003E - The role is to make decisions on behalf of the person, not to provide medical advice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe medical power of attorney / substitute decision maker ensures that someone trusted can make healthcare decisions that align with the person\u0027s wishes when they are no longer able to do so themselves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A medical power of attorney / substitute decision maker allows a person to appoint someone to make healthcare decisions on their behalf if they lose decision-making capacity.","The appointed medical decision maker must make decisions that reflect the person\u0027s known wishes and values.","A medical power of attorney / substitute decision maker takes effect only when the person loses capacity to make their own healthcare decisions."],"references":["Australian Government. Advance care directive. [online]. 2024. [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/topics/palliative-care/planning-your-palliative-care/advance-care-direc...","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92564"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18964"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92564"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T15:10:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T15:10:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11698"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110293"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t